The paper deals with the space complexity of recognizing nonregular languages by various types of machines, including deterministic, nondeterministic, and alternating machines. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) category. Additionally, the paper considers the space complexity of these machines in the context of real-time computation, which could also place it in the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) category. The paper also discusses the use of pushdown automata, which could relate to the Data Structures (cs.DS) category. The paper provides lower bounds for the space complexity of these machines, which could relate to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of unary inputs, which could relate to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category.
